@node Phoneformat "The Phone-file documentation."


		The current Phone-file format supports:

		·Names. 
		·Address string.
		·Home and Mobile phonenumbers.
		·E-mail Address.
		·CPR-number (Format: DDMMYY) 
		·Unlimited comments. (Ain't no novel gonna be written here!!! :·)  
		·Encrypted comments. (Use PGP for Top secret material!)


		@{B}This is mainly for developers and other tech-interested.@{UB} 

	@{u}Here is a listing of a complete Phone-file:@{uu}

	PM5000 01 Oct 1996 Phonemaster V5.42ß ©'96 by Fini 'Warp' Alring.
	#N
	Bill Gates
	#A
	Highway 666, The moon!
	#P
	555-264722
	#M
	555-8544-5
	#I
	Micronerd@Microbrain.dk
	#D
	240845
	#C
	This file should NOT be taken serious!!! Ha!
	Comment number two!!!
	Three!
	4!
	#E
	To the moon you go!


	@{u}Here is a listing of my own Phone-file:@{uu}	


	PM5000 08 Apr 1997 Phonemaster V5.56 ©'1997 by Fini 'Warp' Alring.
	#N
	Fini A. Alring
	#A
	Hřjsgĺrds allé 55, 2900 Hellerup, Denmark.
	#P
	+45 39682845
	#M
	+45 40277142
	#I
	fini.alring@netmedia.dk
	#D
	231277
	#C
	Handle: Warp.  Group: GiGA Produtions.
	The author of Phonemaster!!!  =ß·D
	Also author of GiGA Stereogram Generator.
	#X273203922080320592208922081320803208132011320213201232074320
	#E

	@{u}Here are the codes, and their meaning:@{uu}

	#N - Full name.
	#A - Full Address.
	#P - Phone number.
	#M - Mobile number.
	#I - E-mail address. (I = Internet!)
	#D - Date of birth (DDMMYY)
	#C - Start of Comment-block. - Use #E to end, or PM5 will go Dead!
	#X - Encrypted comment. (Must be inside a comment block!)
	#E - End of comment-block statement.  

	@{i}I suggest you follow the order of apperance above, just to be on the safe side ;-D @{ui}

	But comments can be put anywhere in the file, as long you close with #E statement.
	
	If you plan to use Phone-files elsewhere, encrypted comments should be ingnored.
	But I will give the De/Encryptor, if you plan to make use of encrypted comments.
	(Ofcoz only if I get atleast a beta version, to check that you are serious).
	Also note that the #X tag is the only tag which is on the same line as the data.

 @{u}Phone-File ID:@{uu}


	If you want to reckognise Phone-files, in Dopus or the like,
	look for 'PM5' at the top of the file, these Chars won't be changed EVER!
	
	I write PM5000 in every Phone-file, but the 000's might be used to 
	ID future Phone-files, which might need another way of reading etc... 
	And what is 24bit of storage today? ß·D


@endnode
